In Indonesia, after the earthquake, more than 100 prisoners escaped from prison
More than 100 prisoners have escaped from a prison in Indonesia’s Central Sulawesi province.
Escape became possible after two powerful earthquakes on the island of magnitude 7.2 and 7.4.
According to the newspaper The Jakarta Post, the incident occurred on September 28, when the prisoners in the prison of Palu demanded their release in connection with the tremors.
More than 340 inmates rioted and set the facility on fire.
Police officers who arrived at the scene partially took control of the situation, but more than 100 people escaped from prison.
The building itself has been severely damaged and guards are having difficulty holding prisoners.
The number of victims of the earthquake and tsunami that occurred on the island of Sulawesi increased to 832 people.
As a result, it is still not possible to establish transport, electricity and communications with some areas of the island.
"The Golden Pearl" for "Extreme Realism"
For the third time in history, the San Sebastian International Film Festival recognized the Spanish film as the best film of the year.
The main award - "Golden Shell" - was awarded to the drama "Between the Two Seas" directed by Isaki Lacuesta.
This film with almost documentary realism tells the difficult story of the life of two brothers in the Spanish coastal province of Cadiz - Lacuesta presented a continuation of his 2006 film "The Legend of Time".
At the awards ceremony of the film festival in San Sebastian, the creators of the Argentine thriller Red were honored, which was awarded in several nominations at once.
Benjamin Naistat was announced as director of the year, Pedro Sotero was awarded for camera work, and Dario Grandinetti was recognized as the best actor.
The actress of the year at the San Sebastian Film Festival was Pia Thielta from Norway.
The jury praised her participation in the film "Blind Spot" - a drama about the life of one family after the suicide attempt of her daughter.
The film was the directorial debut of the Swedish actress Tuva Novotna.
In the nomination "best script" the victory was shared by the films "Julie" and "Faithful Man".
The special prize of the jury was awarded to the Philippine crime drama Alpha: The Right to Kill.
Dizziness, tears and laughter
The festival in San Sebastian is called one of the main cultural events in Spain and one of the most important European film competitions.
About his impressions of the festival Euronews told the owner of the "Golden Shell" Director Isaki Lacuesta:
It was wonderful!
We came here with the whole team and of course we experienced dizzying moments, tears, laughter.
We're happy.
We started making this movie 14 years ago, it was a very long job, and most importantly for me, we didn’t want to stop.
Now is the time for joy and gratitude.
As Euronews correspondent Carlos Marlaska notes, Isaki Lacuesta's film organically fit into the collection of paintings that received the Golden Shells, "but the festival in San Sebastian did not do without unexpected, sometimes shocking decisions of the jury, which is sometimes even called the hallmark of the competition."
