AfG became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant “Alternative for Germany” is breaking another record of popularity, and Angela Merkel’s ratings are falling.
Apparently, the people of Germany began to get seriously tired of the immigration policy of Angela Merkel, thanks to which the country became a coveted target for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
This is most clearly evidenced by recent polls, according to which the anti-immigrant party “Alternative for Germany” is becoming more popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, the AfD broke another record, rising to second place in the rating of popular sympathies.
Right-wing conservatives with 17 percent of popularity managed to beat the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The gap of one percentage point can be attributed to a statistical error, but it should be noted that the AdH created in 2013 from a small group of Eurosceptic economists managed to turn into a serious political force.
The leadership in the overall standings continues to be held by the ruling CSU/CDU bloc, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points - back in April, support for Angela Merkel's bloc was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German chancellor, who heads the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also declining.
Today, 48% of Germans support Angela Merkel, which is 7% lower than last year.
We should add that the Social Democrats are followed by the Greens (15%), the Left (11%) and the Liberals (10%).
Evolution of "Alternatives"
The Alternative for Germany party was founded in September 2012 on the basis of the Alternative Choice 2013 group, which included people from the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government’s course, but at first only dealt with economic issues, including the euro and interaction within the EU.
At the same time, the group opposed Germany's "sponsorship" of weak EU economies, did not exclude the possibility of a return to the German mark and the country's complete exit from the European Union.
Amid the deepening immigration crisis, the AfD’s political platform has expanded.
In 2013, the group formed a full-fledged party, which occupied a niche of eurosceptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017, the AfD managed to break into the Bundestag for the first time, receiving 94 seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of the “Alternative for Germany” won seats in the European Parliament.
