Macedonian opposition leader refuses to vote in referendum
In Macedonia on Sunday, September 30, a referendum is held on the issue of an intergovernmental agreement with Greece on the renaming of the Republic of Macedonia.
Citizens are invited to answer one question: “Do you support EU and NATO membership by accepting the agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Hellenic Republic?”
Nevertheless, the leader of the leading opposition party "Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization - Democratic Party for Macedonian National Unity" (VMRO-DPMNE) Christian Mitskosky said that he would not vote in the referendum.
As explained by the press Secretary of the party Naum Stoilkovsky, Mitskosky decided to abstain from voting to express his disagreement with the contract, which he considers “delicious”.
According to the spokesman, the current referendum resolves the issue of renaming the country and nothing more, while the strategic goal of the party is to achieve membership in NATO and the EU.
A week ago, Macedonian President Gheorghe Ivanov refused to participate in the referendum on September 30.
He explained that he chose the name for the country 27 years ago in a referendum on independence. The Macedonian leader considers the renaming of the country a negative factor.
“A new semi-sovereign state is being created with a new name,” Ivanov said.
The agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav Republic - the Republic of North Macedonia - was signed by the Foreign Ministers of Macedonia and Greece on June 17 this year during a solemn ceremony on the shore of Lake Prespa, along which the border between the two countries passes.
This treaty should resolve a long-standing dispute about the name of the country, as well as Skopje’s path to NATO and the EU.
